{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_oliver_ver01/data/sn83045462/00280600532/1930112301/0062.xml":{"full_text":"RADIO OPENING\nGREATEROUTIETS\nManufacturers CurtaH Few\nExpenditures, Despite\nDepression.\nBY MARTIN CODEL.\nThrough the medium of broadcast\ning. the only branch of radio that is\nprogressing full sails up and full speed\nahead through the stilly sea of business,\nthv radio manufacturing industry pro\nposes to develop new and permanent\n-\u2022outlets for its products.\nDealt a severe Mow by the current\nbusiness depression, several of the far\nsighted makers of radios and radio\nmaterials see strong trade prospects in\nforeign trade. They intend using long\ndistance broadcasting in the develop\nment of that trade, hitherto scarcely\nsummed because of the greater and\nmore immediate profits that have ex\nisted in the domestic market\nThe sale of radio receiving\u2014and some\ntransmitting\u2014equipment is the real\nmotive behind recent applications to the\nFederal Radio Commission for permis\nsion to utilize the relay short waves for\nsending American-staged sponsored\nprograms for rebroadcasting abroad,\nparticularly in Latin American coun\ntries. The sponsors would be Ameri\ncan radio manufacturers, and the pro\ngrams, though staged in this country,\nwould be suited to the particular taste\nat the countries of destination.\nFew Curtail Expenses.\nIt is a noteworthy fact that few. if\nany. of the radio manufacturers have\ncurtailed their expenditures for broad\ncasting, in spite of the business let\ndown. The reason may either be sat\nisfaction with the pulling power of ra\ndio or an appreciation of the fact that\nthey (the manufacturers) have too\ngreat a stake in the maintenance of\nprogram excellence to allow It to dete\nriorate by failure to support broad\nlasting\nAt any rate, the radio manufacturers\n\u2022Mount far more than any other single\nindustry for the Income of the chains,\nwhose joint income, exclusive of profits\nfrom the sale of their program talent,\nhas reached $18,798,359 for the first\nnine months of this year, to compare\nwith $18,729,571 for the whole of 1929.\nCertainly there is no philanthropy in\nthe desire to broadcast special pro\ngrams for reception in foreign coun\ntries. The real motive is the creation\nand development of foreign markets\nfor radios, and also for other American\nmade goods. The radio makers believe\nthey can repeat abroad, particularly in\nthe countries of Latin America, which\nla a natural sphere of trade and where\npurchasing power is normally quite\nhigh, the history of American radio\nfirst, the offering of fine programs, and\nthen the creation of a desire among the\npopulace to acquire the Instruments for\nhewing them.\nSince the business depression is world\nwide in scope, the American export\ntrade in radio is lagging along with the\ndomestic trade. The latter is now\nmarked by the losses or extremely low\nearnings currently revealed by some of\nthe leading manufacturers. Radio Cor\nporation of America, for example, re\nported a net loss of nearly $1,000,000\nfar the third quarter of 1930.\nTurn to Other Lines.\nSome of the radio makers are tum\ni lag to other lines to diversify their\noutput, and thus we find them produc\ning electric refrigerators, home talking\npicture equipment, electric clocks, com\nbination broadcast and short-wave re\nceivers, midget sets and a variety of\nother products. But even here they are\nmeeting the sales resistance felt in al\nmost all other lines of business due to\nthe general depression.\nThere is a conviction among the more\nalert and enterprising leaders of the\nradio Industry that even whan the do\nmestic depression is overcome they\nmust make the export trade an integral\nfactor in all their production calcula\ntions. just as does the automotive in\ndustry.\nA few awoke early to the foreign\nmarket possibilities, but all too f-./.\nBo far this year\u2014that is, tor the first\nnine month*\u2014the American export trade\nin radio has amounted to $13,962,635.\nThough the last three months are the\nbast for the export business, there seems\nto be little likelihood that the 1929\ntotal of $21,122,027 will be exceeded or\neven reached at the end of this year.\nFuture years, however, should see the\nfigure swell enormously. Certainly the\npresent income from export is a baga\ntelle in the total volume of radio busi\nness in this country that has amounted\nto anywhere from $500,000,000 to\n$1,000,000,000 at retail annually.\nLIGHTHOUSE KEEPERS\nTO BE GIVEN RADIOS\nDots of Barth Extending From\n0\nCoasts of Florida to Have Means\nof Communication.\nKEY WEST, Fla. (IP). \u2014No more will\nthe lonely lighthouse keepers on Dry\nTortugas and other far-flung dots of\nx earth extending southwestward from\nthe Florida mainland be wllthout com\nmunication during a storm.\nThe Government is to install radio\ntelephones between the keys and the\nmainland.\nJ. L. Preston, a radio expert, and\nHarry B. Haskins, superintendent of\nlighthouses, have already begun instal\nlation work at Dry Tortugas, and a\nsimilar outfit will be placed in opera\ntion here.\nt RADIO AIDS POLICE\nGrime Detection by Air Much Util\nized in Europe.\nLONDON UP. \u2014Radio is rapidly on\nthe way to becoming the world\u2019s police-\nI man. judging by reports from Europe,\nwhere many short-wave stations are\nbeing erected to assist the police In\ntracking criminals.\nIn England particularly radio is being\ncalled upon exclusively for criminal de\ntection work. France is also conteni\nctating the use of the famous Eiffel\nb Tower short-wave station to act as the\n\u2022enter for an extensive radio service.\nCLASSICS WANTED\nDural Radio Tens Prefer High-\nType Music.\nCHICAGO UP- \u2014Listeners on farms\nitamand music classics instead of \"home\nlanes.\" Frank E. Mullen, director of\nagricultural programs for N. B. C., has\nKroed by experience.\nIn the National Farm and Home hour\nbroadcast regularly by N. B. C. are\nfeatured such numbers as the quartet\nfrom \u201cRlgoletto,\u201d the \u201cFlower Bong\"\nfrom \"Carmen\" and a medley from the\n4 Metropolitan Opera.\nToting Series to Be Beaumed.\nWith the political smoke clouds\ncleared away, the National League of\nWomen Voters is making ready to re\nsume its annual voters\u2019 service series\nover a network of the N. B. C. \"The\nVoter's Personal Stake in Government\"\nwill be the genera] theme of the non\ncampaign year\u2019s offerings, which will be\npresented for a half hour weekly be\nginning January 6 and continuing\nthrough May.\nHouston Has Four Stations.\nHOUSTON, Tex. (ip.\u2014 With the an\nnouncement. \"This is station KXYZ,\nHouston, Tex.\u201d this city\u2019s fourth radio\nstation recently was opened. There\nwas no inaugural ceremony.\nToday on the Radio\n\n(All time p.m., unless otherwise indicated.)\nLocal Stations\nwnp 315.6 Meters.\nWnL 950 Kilocycles.\nB:ooa\u2014Tone pictures.\n9:00a \u2014Children\u2019s hour.\n10:00 to 10:30a\u2014Woodwind Ensemble.\n12:00\u2014Miniature recital.\n12:15\u2014National Oratorio Boclety.\nI:l\u00df\u2014Armchair Quartet and Godfrey\nLudlow, violinist.\n1:30 \u2014Neopolltan Days.\n2:oo\u2014Moonshine and Honeysuckle.\n2:3o\u2014Roxy Symphony Concert.\n3:oo\u2014The Pilgrims.\n3:30\u2014Southland Sketches.\n4:00 \u2014Religious service by Dr. S.\nParkes Cadman.\ns:oo\u2014Mixed chorus and orchestra.\n6:oo\u2014Catholic hour.\n7:00 \u2014Big Brothers\u2019 Club.\n7:30 \u2014Correct time.\n7:3l\u2014Capitol \"Family.\u201d\n8:30 \u2014Choral orchestra.\n9:00\u2014\u201cOur Government,\u201d by David\nLawrence.\n9:ls\u2014Marie Healy, soprano, and or\nchestra.\n10:15\u2014Goldkettes Orchestra.\n10:45\u2014Sunday at Seth Parker\u2019s.\n11:15\u2014Weather forecast.\n11:16 \u2014Sam Herman, xylophonist.\n11:30 to 12:00\u2014Russian Cathedral\nChoir.\nEarly Program Tomorrow.\n6:45a \u2014Tower health exercises.\n8:00a \u2014Phil Cook, comedian.\n8:45a \u2014Morning devotions.\nB:3oa\u2014Chee